Response to reviewers

DYRESM aeration:

Figure 1. DYRESM aeration simulations with the recommended line source diffusor configuration. Increasing the number of ports makes a large difference in the performance of the aerator. Above are a series of model runs where RMSE of the lake temperature range varies with flow rate while the number of plume sources (ports) are held constant at 30. Within each figure pannel, the left most vertical line denotes GELI airflow and the right most line the optimal airflow for the aerator.

Mechanical efficiency:

Figure 2. Efficiency estimates decrease when negative values are not zeroed. Efficiencies (mean +- standard error) of 2012 and 2013 are 1.801+-0.0075 and 2.293+-0.023, respectively. These values generally agree with aeration efficiency reports, and accord with the new DYRESM results of Figure 1.

Dissolved Oxygen at 18 m:

Figure 3. Dissolved oxygen at 18 m decreases faster during mixing but destratification reoxygenates the water column and avoids the late autumn lows of non-mixed years.

Proportion of lake < 2 mg/L O2:

Figure 4. The proportion of Crystal Lake < 2 mg/L O2 was less in mixed years. Average proportion < 2 mg/L averaged: 0.14/d (2011), 0.08/d (2012), 0.06/d (2013), 0.29/d (2014).

Comparing DYRESM parameters (Smith et al. and Gaeta et al.)

Bubble plume mixing simulations of Smith et al. differ considerably from Gaeta et al. Smith et al. reports ~ 25 % less airflow than Gaeta et al.. A comparison of parameters used in simulating the unmixed hydrodynamics of Crystal Lake (2011) reveal Smith et al.s parameter set reproduces the thermal regime of Crystal Lake more accurately than the parameter set of Gaeta et al..

Table 1: DYRESM parameters of Smith et al. and Gaeta et al. The bold font parameters of Gaeta et al. are averages of 6 simulated years (2003-2008). The parameters of 2009 were included in the DYRESM code package but are assumed to not have been used in the manuscript results.

Figure 5. RMSE of compared variables are presented in each figure.

Figure 6. The Gaeta et al. aeration parameters, when used to mix Crystal Lake (2013), do not produce a similar temperature range as reported in their manuscript. At comparable airflows, Smith et al. reduces the Crystal Lake temperature range less than Gaeta. The top row of subfigures is the optimal free airflow of ~ 9 L/s (as determined in Fig. 1), distributed among 30 sources. The bottom row of subfigures is the free airflow of ~ 22 L/s (low mix scenario of Gaeta et al.) distributed among 30 sources.
